 Good morning. We are in Chicago at the AATS annual scientific meeting and I'm thrilled to be here for CTS Net Global with Dr. Gina Portella who is an anesthesiologist by training. Spent 10 years working in Italy before joining the non-governmental organization Emergency International and with that organization she has done extraordinary things. So she's been the medical director of all of their countless activities globally for areas of conflict, war, humanitarian crisis but particularly she has been the director of the Salam Center outside of Khartoum, Sudan which we're going to hear about today that is really doing exceptional work and she even led this through the period of humanitarian crisis in 2023-2024 which I think the UN indicated it was the world's greatest humanitarian crisis that we've seen in our time. To lead the division through that type of crisis is incredible so I have so many things to ask you and I'm so grateful for your joining us here today. Thank you, Emily. Thank you for this opportunity. Dr. Portella, can you just tell us set the stage a little bit about the Salam Center, its location, how it came about and set the landscape a little for our audience who don't know, please. So the Salam Center is a center for cardiac surgery. We built it in Sudan with the idea to bring their free of charge and quality care for a disease that are forgotten and are really an unmet need. So this was the main idea to establish the center and is running now for 2007 and was able, as you mentioned, to keep going also even through the world. So we are quite, let's say, happy about what has been possible. Dr. Portella, I think it's almost impossible to imagine how Emergency International completely funds all of these surgeries free for families from all over the region, not just Sudan, but there are cross-border relationships and agreements that allow patients and families to travel freely and to receive all of this care completely free of charge. It's almost mind-boggling how one organization can manage such a thing. There is partnership though with the government, is that right? True, yes. This partnership is one of the key points, I think, of the success, let's call it a success, of this project. Also if the burden to keep open a cardiac surgery for the organization that is not so big it's quite demanding. But the government is contributing with five million dollars per year, that is more or less, a little bit less than half of the running cost. So that can help us to guarantee this free of charge treatment, not only for the surgical care, but long life. Definitely that partnership is meaningful. So you spoke this morning in our global session on cardiothoracic surgery in low and middle income countries and showed data that revealed outcomes on 8,000 rheumatic heart valvular surgeries that are comparable to any of the standards in Europe, UK, the US. What sort of specific clinical protocols or quality controls or how do you maintain a standard like that with very complex patients coming late and perhaps malnourished and all of the factors that make surgery complex? It's a big effort. You are right. We need very straight protocols. We need a multidisciplinary team quite well trained. We still like to have international team coming, spending quite a good amount of time with us and guaranteeing that the continuity of the approach, the clinical approach, the surgical approach is maintained to make possible not only to improve our way to treat the patient because of course continuity is one of the key points to guarantee the patients to guarantee the patients to have a common approach, a study approach, but also to guarantee the training for the young doctors. We are working a lot with local doctors to make it possible. Moreover, there is a continuous review. The organization monitors the results, monitors the protocols, monitors the process and we often re-discuss our way to work. So this is our, in my opinion, one of the key points. So constantly reassessing and re-evaluating and making changes that are meaningful. Okay. You alluded to the local staff and the training and the reliance really on the local team that runs the center. So we mentioned in the session, the power of Salaam really is in the local DNA, isn't it? And so in the time of conflict, do you think that it was really the investment that's been made in the local team was really critical to keeping the center open and continuing to do surgery, even though you weren't at the, you know, thousand surgeries annually that you normally were doing, you still were operating. We saw 20 to 30 cases of heart surgery per month, which is hard to even imagine under the conditions like the, you know, power outages, the staff constraints, the displacements, all of those issues. So is the local, the local team that you've invested in, how critical are they to this effort? Well, it was exactly that very sad and difficult moment to show him how important it was to invest on them. Not only on matter for capacity, for competence, but also for the heart that they put in the job. This job was possible because they were competent. They were able to work autonomously. Of course, we reduce a lot our number because the security issue was not as simple to keep internationals in the country. And they were able to, let's say, lead the center. The main problem that we have in making that, you know, faster and easier to have these colleagues staying and start to lead, really to lead autonomously, the center is the brain drain on the region. This is something that unfortunately is decreasing a lot, our capacity to really build the future by local staff. That is one of the main problems that we face. Brain drain meaning that you train local teams and then they go elsewhere to local clinicians. They go elsewhere to practice. Sure. Can you imagine that we find out that our nurses that are specialized in training in intensive care, in operating theaters, so at high level, they are recruited without not even having for them any interview. They know they are coming from our center, so they take them as granted as well-trained. In some sense, it's giving us the idea that maybe we do a good job. From the other side, it's a pity because they are not even going, you know, in other African countries or surrounding countries. They are taken by the Gulf countries. So, because, yes, this is a problem because, of course, they are very competitive in terms of money. It's true. Well, that is a particular challenge and related to that one is surgeons. So, we've talked a lot about the restraints of bringing highly specialized staff into a place like Sudan and to make a commitment, almost not a volunteer commitment, but a time away from their home, right? For a period of time. What do you see as the constraints for surgeons coming to work at the Salam Center? I fully understand. It's a constraint because, of course, we ask, if possible, a commitment for some months. You know, ideally, it should be for the first mission, six months, because, as we mentioned, it's a project that has its own approach, its own way to do things, like every center. We understand that it's difficult for a surgeon to leave the commitment for his job, the family and so on. Of course, we pay salaries because we understand the professional needs, of course, are not salaries competitive for private sector or other sector where the surgeon can work and, of course, have different economic rewards. Sure. We haven't solved that problem yet, but we're working on it, haven't we? And just to reinforce, so the Salam Center is always looking for cardiac surgeons who have the ability to take time and to give their skills at the Salam Center if applying and vetted and it is actually not a volunteer position. As you pointed out, there's a stipend to cover that time, but it's really the investment of the longitudinal aspect of it that sometimes is hard, particularly for U.S. surgeons to find, you know, three months or six months of time. And so if you have a solution for that, let us know because we're trying to answer that question. Salam Center is authorized by the Sudanese Medical Specialization Board, so it trains cardiologists, cardiac surgeons, anesthesiologists, and specialized nursing staff. So how do you balance that teaching with the high volume service you're giving? Because we all struggle with, you can do more cases when you're not taking the time to teach and invest in the training? We really think that the training, mainly for postgraduate training, is something should be done together. So the tutoring is a lot on the daily job. So the commitment and the work that we take together, the fellows and the tutors, is doing the job together and then rediscuss the jobs. There is not a separate action between the training and the tutoring and the care. And every day, every day we have medical meetings to rediscuss the case. Weekly we have cases that there are case discussions for difficult cases, for questionable cases. And moreover, we encourage our team to have presentations and to deeply study about specific topics, considering also that about rheumatic heart disease, there is not too much, let's say, competent knowledge about the specific actions like surgery, like anesthesia and so on. Let's say the trainees, let's call them like this, are quite happy and enthusiastic. They are the best, you know, volano, we say in Italy, to keep bringing people and to work together because they feel they are getting knowledge and getting sharing information and so on. It's hard, but it's really part of our job. Actually, we are looking for passionate people to really share knowledge. Definitely. And I understand you've just trained the first female cardiac surgeon in Sudan. Yeah. Her name is Nada. I'm very proud because she's very quiet lady and I have to say she's been very strong and actually she has been working with during the studies. She was with us and she was supposed to stay there six months and then she renew one year. Then she was stuck in during the war. The Sudanese Specialization Board accepted and actually was happy. She was keeping studying with us and now she just graduated and really this is, you know, with other colleagues, but as a lady, of course, I'm more close. Yes, absolutely. Congratulations to her. If you had to identify one key lesson from trying to manage and sustain the Salon Center during the conflict, what's the one lesson or one really defining message, I think, about how you kept that place running during such a devastating crisis? Let me be honest. It was a big, big effort done by all the organization. Because, of course, one key point is that us as organization, we work in world-term areas. So we have long experience in Afghanistan and that helped, you know, helped a lot. The way we approach our centers usually is to have, for example, store to work six months also if the borders are closed suddenly. So that was, you know, already in our DNA in the way to work. To maintain neutrality during the war is another huge effort. Continuous communication with authorities from both sides, being very clear that we don't have any political interest, but we are there just to help people. And that was helping. Then during the war, of course, we went through very big, huge economic effort because everything was missed. And to bring things inside the country was very difficult, we were trying to help also the patients because for the patient was difficult to reach Khartoum. So at the same time, we opened a peripheric clinic to allow the patient to be seen by our doctors and in case to be transferred to the center in case of need. But I have to be honest, as a doctor, I find out that always the organization has a very focused attention in trying to keep the system, the logistic, the safety and everything to allow us to keep working during those critical moments. And working also with cardiac surgery. I never thought to do more cardiac surgery, to be honest. I really was not the project. Right, right. And still you found yourself doing it. That's really interesting thinking about the, like you said, the DNA of emergency working in areas of conflict and how you were ready for that, but yet still had to wrap your mind around such a formidable task to do complex cardiac surgery in a time of conflict. I could talk all day about the work at Salam Center and it reminded me what you were saying about neutrality, that Salam means peace, doesn't it? Yes. And so one of the real striking things to me about Salam is how you've brought patients from all over Sub-Saharan Africa, regardless of the borders and the political conflicts and the geopolitical landscape. Is that because of the connection with the government or despite the connection with the government or how have you managed to get patients across borders the way you do? If I can say it was always thank you to the government because, you know, it doesn't matter what was the government, but always they allowed the patients to come, doesn't matter from which country, they always give us the visa for free for the patient. That is a big help because it is very difficult to move. And actually always when I spoke with my good friend now, the actual Minister of Health, it was really underlined that sometimes this neutrality of medicine that is a need for all of us, doesn't matter who we are, is the best health diplomacy we can put in place. So this was inspiring me in thinking it's true. It's not only a matter of medicine, care of people, but also to connect and maybe to put the ground to build a kind of peace or start to talk together. So this is a point, it's a big point. And it sets the right tone, doesn't it? Anything else that you'd like to add about Salam Center? It's such an incredible place and just a snapshot of it is almost not enough to understand the outstanding work that's being done there. But are there any other messages that you want to get to our audience about Salam Center? I really would like to have more people passionate about this kind of programs because I think to take the challenge to offer free of charge, complex medical care, like cardiac surgery, and to be able also to guarantee a follow-up, long-life follow-up for patients, is something that is in our duty as doctors, because it's impossible that we want it for us, for our families, for our patients in our countries, and we don't give a little bit of us to make it possible in countries that doesn't have it at all. So this is, I think, is something that Salam Center can be a good place to start, keep going about this kind of projects. I think that's an excellent point. I mean, the future of our specialty really isn't solely about technical innovation and other fancy things that we see at meetings like this, but it's about that excellence being accessible to everyone. And Salam and Emergency has done such an incredible job leveling that playing field to provide access to so many patients around Sub-Saharan Africa and then follows them up, as you mentioned, completely free of charge. It's just an incredible place. I just want to bring everyone's attention to a link that we'll provide in the thread that has been done at Salam Center when I visited before the pandemic, but it has a lot of information about the Salam Center and just to be able to see it in the video, I think, is really inspiring. But the real inspiration is you, Dr. Portela, and Emergency and your team. We're so grateful to have you speak with us this morning. Thank you very much. And thank you really to give us the opportunity to share with such an audience this project and these ideas. Thank you. Thank you.